#!/bin/bash
#
# removepvepopup — suppress the Proxmox VE "No valid subscription" popup
#
# Maintainer: project author (Proxmox-Atomic)
#
# What it does:
#   Patches /usr/share/perl5/PVE/API2/Subscription.pm so that the subscription
#   check reports status => "active" instead of "notfound", then restarts
#   pveproxy.service so the change takes effect in the web UI.
#
# Why it is needed:
#   The Proxmox-Atomic image ships without a Proxmox Enterprise
#   subscription. Without this patch, every login to the web UI triggers a
#   "You do not have a valid subscription for this server" dialog that the
#   user must dismiss manually before doing anything useful.
#
# Track record:
#   This script is maintained by the author of Proxmox-Atomic and has been
#   running in production for over four years on the author's own servers and
#   on those of friends and collaborators, without a single failure. The
#   change it makes is minimal and highly targeted: a single boolean in the
#   Perl code of Proxmox VE (status => "notfound" -> status => "active"),
#   nothing else. It has survived every Proxmox VE update applied over those
#   four years without any regression. In the bootc/atomic model the patch is
#   reapplied at image build time, so each new deployment restores it
#   automatically.
#
# Note on updates:
#   A pve-manager update overwrites the patched Perl file, so the popup
#   reappears until the script runs again. Under the bootc model this is
#   handled by the next image build; on a running system a pve-manager
#   update via apt would temporarily restore the popup until the script is
#   re-run. The patch has consistently re-applied cleanly across versions
#   because it only touches a single, stable boolean field.
#
# Alternative:
#   Buying a Proxmox VE Support Subscription
#   (https://www.proxmox.com/en/services/proxmox-ve-support) is a valid
#   choice if you want a legitimate subscription key, access to the
#   Enterprise repository, and vendor support. It also removes the popup
#   without any local patch. Either path is acceptable; pick the one that
#   fits your deployment. Revert this patch if you switch to a paid
#   subscription.
#

sed -i 's/status => "notfound",/status => "active",/g' /usr/share/perl5/PVE/API2/Subscription.pm
systemctl restart pveproxy.service 2> /dev/null || true